SUMMER INSTITUTE IN TROPICAL MEDICINE & PUBLIC HEALTH
=====================================================
The Johns Hopkins School of Hygiene and Public Health
and School of Medicine Presents
THE SUMMER INSTITUTE IN TROPICAL MEDICINE AND PUBLIC HEALTH
July 8-August 30, 1996
This 8-week summer program provides training in tropical medicine and
related public health issues through a multidisciplinary approach.
Students will acquire a scientific basis for preventing, diagnosing,
treating, and controlling tropical health problems. The course is
designed to prepare participants for working in developing countries
with tropical and public health problems. Students will become
familiar with recent advances in diagnostic methodologies in tropical
medicine and public health.
The course includes didactic lectures, seminars, and practical
parasitology laboratory experience which focus on specific tropical
diseases and detailed case studies stressing diagnosis, treatment,
and the implementation of preventive and control measures in tropical
medicine and public health. Distinguished faculty from the Johns
Hopkins School of Hygiene & Public Health and School of
Medicine as well as invitees from National Institutes of Health,
WRAIR, USAMRID, PAHO, and University of Maryland will be presenting
seminars and lectures.
Specific topics to be covered include:
Viral and Arboviral Infections Yellow Fever
Invasive Enteric Infections Cholera
Respiratory Disease Typhus
Viral and Arboviral Infections Shistosomiasis
AIDS and Sexually Transmitted Diseases Rabies
Diarrheal Illnesses/Oral Rehydration Cryptosporidium
Hepatitis (A, B, C, D, G) Malaria
Cysticercosis and Hydatid Disease Bartonellosis
Helminthiasis Tuberculosis
Filariasis Echinoccosis
Leprosy Vector Control
Water Supply and Sanitation Child Survival Nutrition
Maternal and Women's Health Family Planning
The program is targeted towards physicians, research scientists,
public health, medical, and veterinary students as well as staff of
health ministries, regional health departments, research scientists,
international aid organizations, and senior nurses/technicans who
wish to become involved in tropical and public health disease control
programs.
The program can be taken for graduate academic credit, CME credit or
certificate. It has been approved as a prerequisite for the American
Society of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene's Certificate in Clinical
Tropical Medicine and Traveler's Health.
For course brochure, application, tuition and housing fees, or any
other information, please
contact:
Heather Roth
